{{Infobox person | name = Anupama Niranjana | image = File:Anupama Niranjana photo.jpg <!-- just the filename, without the File: or Image: prefix or enclosing [[brackets]] --> | alt = | caption = | birth_name = <!-- only use if different from name -->Venkata Lakshmi | birth_date = <!-- {{Birth date and age|YYYY|MM|DD}} or {{Birth-date and age|birth date†}} -->1934 | birth_place = [[Tirthahalli]] | death_date = <!-- {{Death date and age|YYYY|MM|DD|YYYY|MM|DD}} or {{Death-date and age|death date†|birth date†}} -->1991 | death_place = | nationality = Indian | other_names = | occupation = Doctor, Writer | known_for = | spouse = [[Niranjana (writer)|Niranjana]] }}
'''Anupama Niranjana''' ({{lang-kn|ಅನುಪಮಾ ನಿರಂಜನ}}) (1934&ndash;1991)<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=OjZYf9Xf9bcC&pg=PA382&lpg=PA382&dq=Anupama+Niranjana&source=bl&ots=3QOaUPWoZe&sig=6zI7jEFfSW-Jiih9Hmo6UcHjfrE&hl=en&ei=-kbMTKbuKM-ecfWIlckO&sa=X&oi=book_result&ct=result&resnum=2&ved=0CBsQ6AEwATgK#v=onepage&q=Anupama%20Niranjana&f=false Women writing in India], p. 382.</ref> was a doctor in [[India]] and writer of modern [[Kannada]] fiction and non-fiction.
She advocated the woman's point of view and was one among such writers in Kannada, which includes others like [[Triveni Acharya|Triveni]] and [[M. K. Indira]]. Her novel Runamuktalu has been made into a successful film by [[Puttanna Kanagal]].<ref>[http://www.kamat.com/kalranga/kannada/s9.htm Photo on Kamat's Potpourri ]</ref>
Born Venkatalakshmi, Anupama practiced as a physician in [[Dharwad]] and [[Bangalore]]. Anupama took to writing early in life and wrote several novels and stories dealing with social issues, particularly women's issue.<ref>[http://www.vishvakannada.com/anupama.htm One of her stories]</ref> She was married to the Kannada writer [[Niranjana (writer)|Niranjana]], a leading novelist of the Progressive school of modern [[Kannada literature]]. Their daughters Tejaswini and Seemanthini are well known academicians. Anupama died of cancer. An award has been instituted in her name for women writing in Kannada.<ref>[http://www.hindu.com/2004/05/17/stories/2004051711800500.htm Anupama Award]</ref>
==Major works== {{div col|colwidth=22em}} *''[http://www.worldcat.org/oclc/31453576 Anant Geeth]'' *''Shwetambari'' *''Sneh Pallavi'' *''Runamuktalu'' *''[http://www.worldcat.org/oclc/499802615 Seve]'' *''[http://www.worldcat.org/oclc/499805218 Pushpak]'' *''[http://www.worldcat.org/oclc/25172680 Kanmani]'' *''Odalu'' *''Nenapu: Sihi-Kahi'' *''[http://www.worldcat.org/oclc/31495101 Kallol]'' *''[http://www.worldcat.org/oclc/21334442 Aala]'' *''Mukti Chitra'' *''Madhavi'' *''Ghosha'' *''Nati'' *''Moolamukhi'' (last novel) *''Cancer Jagattu'' *''Taayi magu'' *''Dinakkondu kathe'' (collection of children's stories) {{div col end}}
