{{Infobox language |name=Chagossian Creole |nativename=''kreol Ilwa'' |states=[[Mauritius]], [[Seychelles]] |speakers=1,800 |date=1994 |ref=<ref name="PaC-list">{{cite book |title=Pidgins and Creoles: An introduction |editor-first=Jacques |editor-last=Arends |editor-first2=Pieter |editor-last2=Muijsken |editor-first3=Norval |editor-last3=Smith |chapter=26 An annotated list of creoles, pidgins and mixed languages |author-first=Norval |author-last=Smith |page=347 |publisher=John Benjamins |year=1994 |isbn=978-90-272-5236-4}}</ref> |familycolor=Creole |fam1=[[French-based creole languages|French Creole]] |fam2=[[Bourbonnais Creole]]s |fam3=[[Mauritian Creole]] |isoexception=dialect |glotto=none }}
'''Chagossian creole''' (also ''créole îlois'', ''kreol Ilwa'', or just ''Ilwa'') is a [[French-based creole languages|French-based creole]] that was still spoken in 1994 by the 1,800 or so [[Ilois|Chagossians]], the former inhabitants of the [[Chagos Archipelago]] evicted in the early 1970s. It is currently spoken mainly in [[Mauritius]] and the [[Seychelles]]. There is also a small minority community speaking the language in the [[United Kingdom]].
