{{distinguish|Hoti language}} {{Infobox language |name = Hodï |nativename = Yuwana |region = central Venezuela |speakers = 640 |date = 2007 |ref = e18 |familycolor = American |fam1 = [[Piaroa–Saliban languages|Piaroa–Saliban]] ? |iso3 = yau |glotto = yuwa1244 |glottorefname= Yuwana |notice=IPA }}
The '''Hodï''' (Jodï, Jotí, Hoti) language, also known as '''Yuwana''' (Yoana), '''Waruwaru''', or '''Chikano''' (Chicano), is a small [[unclassified language]] of [[Venezuela]]. Very little is known of it; its several hundred speakers are monolingual hunter-gatherers.
==Classification== No classification of Hodï has yet been established to the satisfaction of linguists.
Attempts have been made to link Hodï with the nearby [[Piaroa–Saliban languages]]. A recent proposal classifies Hodï and (Piaroa–)Saliban as the branches of a single Jodï–Saliban [[macrofamily]].<ref> Labrada, Rosés; Emilio, Jorge (2015). [http://glottolog.org/resource/languoid/id/jodi1234 "Jodi-Saliban"]. ''[[Glottolog|Glottolog 2.7]]''. Jena: Max Planck Institute for the Science of Human History.</ref> However, similarities in vocabulary with the Piaroa–Saliban languages may in fact be due to [[sprachbund]]ing: Henley, Mattéi-Müller and Reid (1996) argue that the apparent [[cognate]]s between Hodï and Piaroa–Saliban are rather [[loanword]]s.
Limited by poor data, Henley et al. argue that Hodï may be related to the [[Nadahup languages]].<ref>Henley, Paul; Marie-Claude Mattéi-Müller y Howard Reid 1996. "Cultural and linguistic affinities of the foraging people of North Amazonia: a new perspective"; ''Antropológica'' 83: 3-37. Caracas.</ref> The only linguist to speak Hodï and [[Piaroa language|Piaroa]], Stanford Zent, has collected more reliable data and argues that it is "probably" related to the Piaroa–Saliban languages.<ref>Zent S & E Zent. 2008. Los Hoti, in Aborigenes de Venezuela, vol. 2, second edition [https://ivic.academia.edu/Zent/Papers/73523/Los_Jodi]</ref>
Since 1985 a relationship to the [[Yanomaman languages]] has also been suggested, in part on the grounds that Hodï shares 20% of its vocabulary with this family,<ref>Migliazzi, Ernesto C. 1985. "Languages of the Orinoco-Amazon region"; H.M.Klein & L. Stark (eds.): ''South American Indian Languages'': 17-139. Austin: University of Texas Press.</ref> but this hypothesis has since been largely rejected.
==Phonology== The first phonological analysis is Vilera (1985).<ref>Vilera Díaz, Diana C. 1985. "Introducción morfológica de la lengua Hoti". Thesis in Anthropology. Caracas: Universidad Central de Venezuela.</ref>
