{{Infobox medical condition (new) | name = Mixed receptive-expressive language disorder | | synonyms = | symptoms = | complications = | onset = | duration = | types = | causes = | risks = | diagnosis = | differential = | prevention = | treatment = | medication = | prognosis = | frequency = | deaths = }} '''Mixed receptive-expressive language disorder''' (DSM-IV 315.32)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://behavenet.com/node/21482|title=Diagnostic criteria for 315.31 Mixed Receptive-Expressive Language Disorder|work=behavenet.com}}</ref> is a [[communication disorder]] in which both the receptive and expressive areas of communication may be affected in any degree, from mild to severe.<ref>{{cite document|url=http://www.sess.ie/sites/all/modules/wysiwyg/tinymce/jscripts/tiny_mce/plugins/filemanager/files/Categories/ASD/16Specific_Speech_and_Language_Disorder.pdf|title=Special Education Support Service: Information on Specific Speech and Language Disorder|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141221232531/http://www.sess.ie/sites/all/modules/wysiwyg/tinymce/jscripts/tiny_mce/plugins/filemanager/files/Categories/ASD/16Specific_Speech_and_Language_Disorder.pdf|archivedate=2014-12-21|df=}}</ref> Children with this disorder have difficulty understanding words and sentences. This impairment is classified by deficiencies in expressive and receptive language development that is not attributed to sensory deficits, nonverbal intellectual deficits, a neurological condition, environmental deprivation or psychiatric impairments.<ref>{{cite journal |doi=10.1177/070674370304800907 |title=Behaviour in Children with Language Development Disorders |journal=The Canadian Journal of Psychiatry |volume=48 |issue=9 |pages=607–14 |year=2016 |last1=Willinger |first1=Ulrike |last2=Brunner |first2=Esther |last3=Diendorfer-Radner |first3=Gabriele |last4=Sams |first4=Judith |last5=Sirsch |first5=Ulrike |last6=Eisenwort |first6=Brigitte }}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |doi=10.1016/j.ijpsycho.2007.10.015 |pmid=18304666 |title=Auditory evoked fields predict language ability and impairment in children |journal=International Journal of Psychophysiology |volume=68 |issue=2 |pages=170–5 |year=2008 |last1=Oram Cardy |first1=Janis E |last2=Flagg |first2=Elissa J |last3=Roberts |first3=Wendy |last4=Roberts |first4=Timothy P.L }}</ref> Research illustrates that 2% to 4% of 5 year olds have mixed receptive-expressive language disorder. This distinction is made when children have issues in expressive language skills, the production of language, and when children also have issues in receptive language skills, the understanding of language. Those with mixed receptive-language disorder have a normal left-right anatomical asymmetry of the planum temporale and parietale. This is attributed to a reduced left hemisphere functional specialization for language. Taken from a measure of cerebral blood flow (SPECT) in phonemic discrimination tasks, children with mixed receptive-expressive language disorder do not exhibit the expected predominant left hemisphere activation.<ref name=pmid15714898>{{cite journal |doi=10.1016/S0010-9452(08)70890-6 |pmid=15714898 |title=Hemispheric Specialization for Language in Children with Different Types of Specific Language Impairment |journal=Cortex |volume=41 |issue=2 |pages=157–67 |year=2005 |last1=Pecini |first1=C |last2=Casalini |first2=C |last3=Brizzolara |first3=D |last4=Cipriani |first4=P |last5=Pfanner |first5=L |last6=Chilosi |first6=A }}</ref> Mixed receptive-expressive language disorder is also known as receptive-expressive language impairment (RELI) or receptive language disorder.<ref name=pmid20813021>{{cite journal |doi=10.1111/j.1469-8749.2010.03750.x |pmid=20813021 |title=Intervention for mixed receptive-expressive language impairment: A review |journal=Developmental Medicine & Child Neurology |volume=52 |issue=11 |pages=994–9 |year=2010 |last1=Boyle |first1=James |last2=McCartney |first2=Elspeth |last3=o'Hare |first3=Anne |last4=Law |first4=James }}</ref>
==Classification== If assessed on the [[Wechsler Adult Intelligence Scale]], for instance, symptoms of mixed receptive-expressive language disorder may show as relatively low scores for Information, Vocabulary and Comprehension (perhaps below the 25th percentile). If a person has difficulty with specific types of concepts, for example spatial terms, such as 'over', 'under', 'here' and 'there', they may also have difficulties with arithmetic, understanding word problems and instructions, or difficulties using words at all.<ref>{{cite journal |doi=10.1016/j.pcl.2007.02.014 |pmid=17543904 |title=Language Disorders in Children: Classification and Clinical Syndromes |journal=Pediatric Clinics of North America |volume=54 |issue=3 |pages=437–67, v |year=2007 |last1=Simms |first1=Mark D }}</ref> They may also have a more general problem with words or sentences, both comprehension and orally. Some children will have issues with pragmatics - the use of language in social contexts as well; and therefore, will have difficulty with inferring meaning. Furthermore, they have severe impairment of spontaneous language production and for this reason, they have difficulty in formulating questions.<ref name=pmid15714898/> Generally, children will have trouble with morphosyntax, which is word inflections. These children have difficulty understanding and applying grammatical rules, such as endings that mark verb tenses (e.g. -''ed''), third-person singular verbs (e.g. I ''think'', he ''thinks''), plurals (e.g. -''s''), auxiliary verbs that denote tenses (e.g. ''was'' running, ''is'' running), and with determiners (''the, a''). Moreover, children with mixed receptive-expressive language disorders have deficits in completing two cognitive operations at the same time and learning new words or morphemes under time pressure or when processing demands are high. These children also have auditory processing deficits in which they process auditory information at a slower rate and as a result, require more time for processing.<ref name=pmid20813021/>
==Related Disorders== Studies show that low receptive and expressive language at young ages was correlated to increased autism symptom severity in children in their early school years.<ref>{{cite journal |doi=10.1016/j.ridd.2011.09.003 |pmid=22093662 |title=Language and communication skills in preschool children with autism spectrum disorders: Contribution of cognition, severity of autism symptoms, and adaptive functioning to the variability |journal=Research in Developmental Disabilities |volume=33 |issue=1 |pages=172–80 |year=2012 |last1=Kjellmer |first1=Liselotte |last2=Hedvall |first2=Åsa |last3=Fernell |first3=Elisabeth |last4=Gillberg |first4=Christopher |last5=Norrelgen |first5=Fritjof }}</ref> Below is a chart depicting language deficits of children on the Autistic Spectrum. This table indicates the lower levels of language processing, receptive/expressive disorders, which is more severe in children with autism. When autistic children speak, they are often difficult to understand, their language is sparse and dysfluent, they speak in single, uninflected words or short phrases, and their supply of words is severely depleted.<ref>{{cite journal |doi=10.1016/S1071-9091(97)80024-1 |pmid=9195665 |title=Language disorders in children with autism |journal=Seminars in Pediatric Neurology |volume=4 |issue=2 |pages=86–92 |year=1997 |last1=Rapin |first1=Isabelle |last2=Dunn |first2=Michelle }}</ref> This leads to limited vocabulary while also having deficits in verbal short term memory.<ref name=pmid18067421>{{cite journal |doi=10.1080/09084280701719203 |pmid=18067421 |title=Learning and Memory Performance of Children with Specific Language Impairment (SLI) |journal=Applied Neuropsychology |volume=14 |issue=4 |pages=255–61 |year=2007 |last1=Riccio |first1=Cynthia A |last2=Cash |first2=Deborah L |last3=Cohen |first3=Morris J }}</ref>
{| class="wikitable" |- ! Aspect of Language !! Lower Level Receptive/Expressive Disorders |- | Comprehension: || |- | Phonology || Very impaired |- | Syntax || Very impaired |- | Semantics || Very impaired |- | Pragmatics || Very impaired |- | Prosody || Very impaired |- | Production: || |- | Phonology || Very impaired |- | Syntax || Very impaired |- | Semantics || Very impoverished |- | Pragmatics || Very impaired |- | Prosody || Often impaired, monotonous, robotics |- | Amount of language || Sparse or absent |- | Fluency || Dysfluent |}
==Management== Children who demonstrate deficiencies early in their speech and language development are at risk for continued speech and language issues throughout later childhood. Similarly, even if these speech and language problems have been resolved, children with early language delay are more at risk for difficulties in phonological awareness, reading, and writing throughout their lives.<ref name=pmid18067421/><ref name=pmid19011122>{{cite journal |doi=10.1177/0022219408326215 |pmid=19011122 |title=Using Early Standardized Language Measures to Predict Later Language and Early Reading Outcomes in Children at High Risk for Language-Learning Impairments |journal=Journal of Learning Disabilities |volume=42 |issue=1 |pages=61–75 |year=2008 |last1=Flax |first1=Judy F |last2=Realpe-Bonilla |first2=Teresa |last3=Roesler |first3=Cynthia |last4=Choudhury |first4=Naseem |last5=Benasich |first5=April }}</ref> Children with mixed receptive-expressive language disorder are often likely to have long-term implications for language development, literacy, behavior, social development, and even mental health problems.<ref name=pmid20813021/> If suspected of having a mixed receptive-expressive language disorder, treatment is available from a speech therapist or pathologist. Most treatments are short term, and rely upon accommodations made within the environment, in order to minimize interfering with work or school. Programs that involve intervention planning that link verbal short term memory with visual/non-verbal information may be helpful for these children.<ref name=pmid18067421/> In addition, approaches such as parent training for language stimulation and monitoring language through the "watch and see" method are recommended. The watch-and-see technique advises children with mixed receptive-expressive language disorder who come from stable, middle-class homes without any other behavioral, medical, or hearing problems should be vigilantly monitored rather than receive intervention. It is often the case that children do not meet the eligibility criteria established through a comprehensive oral language evaluation; and as a result, are not best suited for early intervention programs and require a different approach besides the "one size fits all" model.<ref name=pmid19011122/>
