==Language Structure==
In [[linguistic typology]], a '''subject+object+verb''' ('''SOV''') language is one in which the [[subject (grammar)|subject]], [[object (grammar)|object]], and [[verb]] of a sentence always or usually appear in that order. If [[English language|English]] were SOV, "Sam oranges ate" would be an ordinary sentence, as opposed to the actual [[Standard English]] "Sam ate oranges". (A Grammar of Sunuwar)
<ref>{{cite web |url=https://books.google.co.th/books?id=AYA7CpILphoC&printsec=frontcover&source=gbs_ge_summary_r&cad=0#v=onepage&q&f=false| title=A Grammar of Sunwar |publisher=Dörte Borchers | accessdate=27 August 2018}}</ref>
{| class="wikitable"
! Language !! S !! O !! V
|-
| {{IAST|''Sunuwar''}} || Go || Khamay || Jainu
|-
| {{IAST|''English''}} || I || Rice || Eat
|}
Sunuwar people called "Khangsa" sign language with voice and direct action, for foreign people who don't understand a sunuwar language.

==Area==
Sunuwar language is spoken in villages in [[Dolakha District|Dolakha]], [[Ramechhap District|Ramechhap]] and [[Okhaldhunga District|Okhaldhunga]], about 120 kilometers east of [[Kathmandu]].<ref name="Borchers 1–2" />

==Writing systems==
Though Sunuwar is most commonly written with the [[Devanagari]] script, a native writing system, [[Jenticha]], has seen limited use since the 1940s.

